<div id="content_3" class="content">
  <h4>Things to do in Barbados:</h4>
  <p>For some preliminary information on Barbados, we recommend <a href="http://www.accessbarbados.com/barbados_resort.php">check this out.</a> In addition, please feel free to contact either of us - we were just there and should be able to field any questions.</p>
  <h4>Weather:</h4>
  <p>There isn’t a ton of variation from one month to the next in Barbados. There will be rain, sun, and it will be hot and humid. About 85 during the day and 78 in the evening. Barbados is outside of the hurricane belt so we should be okay - knock on wood!</p>
  <h4>Money</h4>
  <p>Currency is currently $1US = $2Bajan. They take US Dollars - even in the supermarkets. But you will get Bajan money back. Prices for food and groceries are equal to NYC prices. US Products like tampons and bugspray will cost you a bit more - so bring them with you.</p>

  <h4>Stuff to do while there:</h4>
    <p class="detailsPagesImages"><img src="http://juliaandandy.com/images/loveBirds.png" alt="" /><br /><span class="caption">Love Birds perched ontop of Luna Cafe, the restaurant above Little Arches Hotel, this May</span></p>
  <ul>
    <li><em>Nightlife</em> - Most of the literature on the island will tell you about how incredible and hopping St. Lawrence Gap ("the Gap") is... we went and were a little underwhelmed. But after full days in the sun we were usually asleep by 10:30.</li>
    <li><em>Beaches</em> - The beautiful beaches are all public in Barbados and all different on the different ends of the island. We hung out at Sandy Beach (south) in Worthing (right in front of our guest house). It was fantastic and at low tide you could walk out to the reef. Had we had snorkel gear, it probably would have been great. There are also lots of water sports such as surfing and wind surfing. I don’t think you can go wrong - just don’t swim on the east coast (the Atlantic side)... or if you do, be careful... we hear it is dangerous. You can watch world-class surfers at <a href="http://travel.nytimes.com/2009/03/29/travel/29barbados.html?pagewanted=all">Soup Bowl</a> on the East Side.  </li>
    <li><em>Non-beach nature</em> - in the following order: <a href="http://www.uncommoncaribbean.com/2011/02/17/on-site-barbados-exploring-the-craggy-north-shore/">North Shore Cliffs</a> (rugged and amazing), <a href="http://www.huntesgardensbarbados.com/">Hunte’s Garden</a> (the life’s work of the completely eccentric expat, Anthony... try his rum punch!), <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bathsheba,_Saint_Joseph,_Barbados">Bathsheba</a> (hilly, quaint, and beautiful... drive along the beach and enjoy), and <a href="http://www.graemehall.com/index.php">Graeme Hall</a> (partially closed, but get a cappuccino and/or rum punch and feed the huge tilapia).</li>
    <li><em>Oistins</em> - see you there on Friday evening... deliciously fresh fish plates for $15US and cheap beers.</li>
    <li><em>Restaurants</em> - <a href="http://www.tidesbarbados.com/">Tides</a> (Shmancy... located on the West Coast...beautiful spot and runner up for our wedding), <a href="http://www.littlearches.com/dining-overview.html ">Cafe Luna</a> at Little Arches (runner up for our wedding... amaze), <a href="http://www.tripadvisor.ca/Restaurant_Review-g147266-d1630479-Reviews-Surfer_s_Bay-Christ_Church_Barbados.html">Surfer's Bay Bar and Grill</a> (cool), <a href="http://www.champersbarbados.com/">Champers</a> (recommended by those "in the know"- on our list of places to try), <a href="http://www.tripadvisor.co.uk/Restaurant_Review-g666622-d1770852-Reviews-Shakers_Bar_Grill-Rockley_Christ_Church_Barbados.html">Shakers</a> (recommended by those "in the know" - on our list of places to try), <a href="http://www.thelonestar.com/aboutus/">Lone Star</a> (recommended by those “in the know” - on our list), <a href="http://www.chefette.com/">Chefette</a> (Barbados’ McDonalds... try the roti!).</li>
    <li>Mont Gay Rum Disillery Tour, Concord Tour, Golfing and <a href="http://www.tripadvisor.com.sg/Attractions-g147262-Activities-Barbados.html">lots more</a>...</li>
  </ul>

